title: For Sale:  Remington 700 BDL Carbine 308 Rare Lst Yr Near New
postcontent: Extremely Rare lst Year Production (1962) Factory 20" barrel Carbine as they are now called by Remington collectors. Made in June 1962 this gun is almost 55 yrs old and is in more or less pristine condition. Production began for the 700 series in 1962 and this fine example has a 4 digit serial number. In 62 only 771 were produced in .308 which by that time had only been around for a short time. Site hood shown comes wit the gun but appears to be a replacement (unknown) Both blue and wood are in at least 90% condition with only light handling marks. The floor plate and trigger guard have some light scratches shown in pics (hopefully) but none significant. Thee are no non factory holes, no cracks, no splits and no touch up.. Front and rear site are in place as is a Weaver scope base. As was the custom in the 60's someone put a little gold paint into the factory lettering; this should come out with a stiff tooth brush. The correct alum. factory butt plate also has the finish overspray (factory) and it has not peeled indicating very little use or having been handled. This gun is triply collectable: low 4 digit serial number and lst year production and a desirable cal of which few were made or sold in the 700 which were also in their infancy.

title: For Sale:  Better than new: UTAS UTS-15 tactical bullpup 15 round Shotgun
postcontent:
This UTS-15 was acquired new last year for review on Gear-Report.com and sent to UTAS for all the latest upgraded parts.It is true that some of the early UTS15 models had issues, which spawned a lot of negative reviews. However, since sending this unit back to the factory for all of the updated/upgraded parts, it has functioned flawlessly and is a joy to shoot. Review shooting is done, so it needs a new home. It is very lightly used and looks practically new. Comes with box with anything that was in the box from the factory. This is my favorite bullpup shotgun of all on the market because it is functional, proven and practical. I would take this one over a KSG since it runs so well. I won't even consider a DP-12 since, to be honest, the whole concept of 2 barrels is gimmicky and lacks practical application, while the manual of arms (cock once, shoot twice) is bizarre and impractical. The UTS-15 has 2 magazine tubes, which is far more beneficial. Who wouldn't want 14+1 rounds, with the ability to feed from one tube or the other, or automatic alternating? The UTS-15's manual of arms and features are made for defense, not to look "tacticool".
From Wikipedia:"The UTAS UTS-15 is a bullpup 12 gauge pump-action shotgun with two 7-round magazine tubes that can feed in an alternating or selecting pattern. The UTS-15 has a 28.3” overall length with an 18.5” barrel, chambered for 2½”, 2¾”, and 3” magnum ammunition. Constructed primarily of fiber reinforced injection molded polymer, the UTS-15 weighs 6.9 lbs. Additionally, there is a top mounted picatinny rail for the mounting of a wide variety of both iron and optical sights, coupled with Beretta style barrel threading for choke tubes."
Don't waste your time with low-ball or trade offers. Unless a trade is very heavily in my favor, then I won't even consider it.Strongly prefer a face to face sale in Burlington, NC. I am willing to ship to your FFL at your expense ONLY if payment is made with a USPS money order.  I had a rather convincing prospective buyer try to sucker me on a remote deal with payment by some othe means. Not dealing with that crap again.
